00:00:59.560 --> 00:01:00.560 align:middle line:84%
>>GREGG BRADEN: George,
it's an honor to be here,

00:01:00.560 --> 00:01:03.100 align:middle line:84%
and I'm really excited to talk
about this material today.

00:01:03.100 --> 00:01:04.030 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: I love you.

00:01:04.030 --> 00:01:05.280 align:middle line:90%
I have always loved your work.

00:01:05.280 --> 00:01:06.363 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Well, thank you.

00:01:06.363 --> 00:01:08.540 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I mean, it's
just thought provoking.

00:01:08.540 --> 00:01:10.210 align:middle line:90%
How did this all start for you?

00:01:10.210 --> 00:01:11.340 align:middle line:84%
Let's go back to the
beginning of Gregg Braden.

00:01:11.340 --> 00:01:12.600 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Well, you want to
go back to the beginning?

00:01:12.600 --> 00:01:14.140 align:middle line:84%
We're filming in
Denver, Colorado,

00:01:14.140 --> 00:01:16.030 align:middle line:84%
and it began right here
in Denver, Colorado

00:01:16.030 --> 00:01:17.545 align:middle line:90%
or in the Rocky Mountain area.

00:01:17.545 --> 00:01:18.211 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Mm-hmm.

00:01:18.211 --> 00:01:20.900 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: I was-- a
lot of our viewers

00:01:20.900 --> 00:01:22.740 align:middle line:84%
don't know this--
behind the scenes.

00:01:22.740 --> 00:01:25.410 align:middle line:84%
I worked in the defense
industry during the last years

00:01:25.410 --> 00:01:28.194 align:middle line:84%
of the Cold War, a
very frightening time--

00:01:28.194 --> 00:01:28.860 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Indeed.

00:01:28.860 --> 00:01:31.010 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: --in the
history of our world

00:01:31.010 --> 00:01:34.110 align:middle line:84%
when the two superpowers at
the time did the unthinkable

00:01:34.110 --> 00:01:39.620 align:middle line:84%
and actually created-- they
spent the energy, the manpower,

00:01:39.620 --> 00:01:44.340 align:middle line:84%
the resources, the technology to
create the weapons to microwave

00:01:44.340 --> 00:01:46.300 align:middle line:84%
the earth many times
over in the event

00:01:46.300 --> 00:01:48.045 align:middle line:84%
that a nuclear
war ever occurred.

00:01:48.045 --> 00:01:49.069 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Wow.

00:01:49.069 --> 00:01:50.860 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: It was during
that time, George--

00:01:50.860 --> 00:01:52.880 align:middle line:84%
if you can imagine,
I found myself

00:01:52.880 --> 00:01:54.700 align:middle line:84%
working behind the
scenes supporting,

00:01:54.700 --> 00:02:00.470 align:middle line:84%
writing software for the missile
program, supporting that effort

00:02:00.470 --> 00:02:01.550 align:middle line:90%
by day.

00:02:01.550 --> 00:02:04.790 align:middle line:84%
And by night-- ever
since I was young,

00:02:04.790 --> 00:02:08.550 align:middle line:84%
I've been a scholar of some of
our most ancient and cherished

00:02:08.550 --> 00:02:10.669 align:middle line:84%
spiritual traditions
and some of the most

00:02:10.669 --> 00:02:13.310 align:middle line:90%
mysterious texts of our past.

00:02:13.310 --> 00:02:16.630 align:middle line:84%
And I have felt, for a
very long time, George,

00:02:16.630 --> 00:02:21.040 align:middle line:84%
that if we knew where
to look in the past,

00:02:21.040 --> 00:02:24.320 align:middle line:84%
that we would find
the key and perhaps

00:02:24.320 --> 00:02:27.230 align:middle line:84%
a message from
our ancestors that

00:02:27.230 --> 00:02:30.680 align:middle line:84%
would help us to transcend
the differences that

00:02:30.680 --> 00:02:32.750 align:middle line:84%
have led to the great
wars of the 20th

00:02:32.750 --> 00:02:35.720 align:middle line:84%
and now the 21st century and,
at that time, the kind of war

00:02:35.720 --> 00:02:37.300 align:middle line:90%
that I was supporting.

00:02:37.300 --> 00:02:39.810 align:middle line:84%
So it was during
that time that I

00:02:39.810 --> 00:02:45.220 align:middle line:84%
began a search and a research
of comparative traditions

00:02:45.220 --> 00:02:47.170 align:middle line:84%
helping us to
understand our origins.

00:02:47.170 --> 00:02:50.610 align:middle line:84%
Because, again, my
thinking was if we

00:02:50.610 --> 00:02:54.490 align:middle line:84%
could find a way to show
beyond any reasonable doubt,

00:02:54.490 --> 00:02:59.550 align:middle line:84%
beyond the superficial,
outward demonstrations that we

00:02:59.550 --> 00:03:02.050 align:middle line:90%
are actually-- we are one.

00:03:02.050 --> 00:03:07.470 align:middle line:84%
And for some people, it's a very
New Age-sounding hope or wish.

00:03:07.470 --> 00:03:09.390 align:middle line:84%
But I think there's
a lot of power

00:03:09.390 --> 00:03:12.250 align:middle line:84%
in showing that that
unification is possible,

00:03:12.250 --> 00:03:14.650 align:middle line:84%
helping us to transcend
those differences.

00:03:14.650 --> 00:03:19.090 align:middle line:84%
So my journey began
to take me back

00:03:19.090 --> 00:03:22.094 align:middle line:84%
into older and older
and older texts,

00:03:22.094 --> 00:03:23.510 align:middle line:84%
cutting through
the red tape and--

00:03:23.510 --> 00:03:24.520 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You were almost
obsessed with it, weren't you?

00:03:24.520 --> 00:03:25.728 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: --in the religions.

00:03:25.728 --> 00:03:28.690 align:middle line:90%
Well, I would say passionate.

00:03:28.690 --> 00:03:30.651 align:middle line:90%
I prefer passion over obsession.

00:03:30.651 --> 00:03:32.400 align:middle line:84%
My wife would probably
say I was obsessed.

00:03:32.400 --> 00:03:33.510 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:03:33.510 --> 00:03:35.760 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Because the
clues-- every time

00:03:35.760 --> 00:03:38.920 align:middle line:84%
I would find a clue, George, and
I'd think, OK, maybe this is it

00:03:38.920 --> 00:03:40.780 align:middle line:84%
and then it's not going
to go anywhere else,

00:03:40.780 --> 00:03:42.100 align:middle line:84%
it would open the door
to something else.

00:03:42.100 --> 00:03:42.440 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Another clue.

00:03:42.440 --> 00:03:44.356 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: And open the
door to something else.

00:03:44.356 --> 00:03:45.900 align:middle line:84%
And that led me
from the textbooks

00:03:45.900 --> 00:03:47.210 align:middle line:90%
onto a series of journeys.

00:03:47.210 --> 00:03:50.156 align:middle line:84%
My first journey was
in Egypt in 1986.

00:03:50.156 --> 00:03:51.780 align:middle line:84%
And what I found in
Egypt on the temple

00:03:51.780 --> 00:03:56.910 align:middle line:84%
walls led me into the highlands
of the Andes Mountains

00:03:56.910 --> 00:04:01.040 align:middle line:84%
of Southern Peru, which directed
me right into the Tibetan

00:04:01.040 --> 00:04:04.320 align:middle line:84%
Plateau in the temples and
the monasteries in Tibet.

00:04:04.320 --> 00:04:07.620 align:middle line:84%
As a scientist, my
thinking is-- I'll

00:04:07.620 --> 00:04:09.120 align:middle line:84%
speak about myself
personally-- if I

00:04:09.120 --> 00:04:14.020 align:middle line:84%
could find the information
least disturbed

00:04:14.020 --> 00:04:16.730 align:middle line:84%
by the modern world, that's
where it will be most intact.

00:04:16.730 --> 00:04:18.516 align:middle line:90%
And to go to those places--

00:04:18.516 --> 00:04:19.141 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:04:19.141 --> 00:04:19.570 align:middle line:90%
You had to.

00:04:19.570 --> 00:04:21.861 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: --you've got to
make the effort to get there.

00:04:21.861 --> 00:04:25.020 align:middle line:84%
They're some of the most
magnificent, beautiful, remote,

00:04:25.020 --> 00:04:27.790 align:middle line:84%
isolated, pristine places
remaining on the world.

00:04:27.790 --> 00:04:29.690 align:middle line:90%
Did I say remote, by the way?

00:04:29.690 --> 00:04:30.870 align:middle line:90%
Because they are.

00:04:30.870 --> 00:04:33.380 align:middle line:84%
But it's in the monasteries
and the nunneries

00:04:33.380 --> 00:04:35.460 align:middle line:84%
where many of these
texts are preserved.

00:04:35.460 --> 00:04:37.350 align:middle line:84%
And they've been
largely forgotten.

00:04:37.350 --> 00:04:38.880 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Truly amazing texts.

00:04:38.880 --> 00:04:40.220 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Well, they are.

00:04:40.220 --> 00:04:43.840 align:middle line:84%
So as I began my
search, my thinking

00:04:43.840 --> 00:04:49.900 align:middle line:84%
was, if we could really
pin down our origins--

00:04:49.900 --> 00:04:53.630 align:middle line:84%
the science, the best
science of the 21st century

00:04:53.630 --> 00:04:55.920 align:middle line:84%
is now overturning so
many of Darwin's ideas.

00:04:55.920 --> 00:04:58.270 align:middle line:84%
And by the way, Darwin
was open to that.

00:04:58.270 --> 00:05:01.270 align:middle line:84%
He was willing for
his ideas to fall.

00:05:01.270 --> 00:05:02.870 align:middle line:84%
He viewed them as
stepping stones

00:05:02.870 --> 00:05:05.140 align:middle line:90%
toward greater understandings.

00:05:05.140 --> 00:05:07.170 align:middle line:90%
So Darwin was OK with that.

00:05:07.170 --> 00:05:14.060 align:middle line:84%
And I began to see a connection
in the texts that was not

00:05:14.060 --> 00:05:16.910 align:middle line:84%
accounted for in the
theories of evolution,

00:05:16.910 --> 00:05:20.377 align:middle line:84%
and it is a connection that
is very controversial today.

00:05:20.377 --> 00:05:22.960 align:middle line:84%
Now Darwin didn't have access
to the tools and the technology.

00:05:22.960 --> 00:05:25.889 align:middle line:84%
He certainly didn't have the DNA
databases that we have today.

00:05:25.889 --> 00:05:26.680 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Of course.

00:05:26.680 --> 00:05:28.360 align:middle line:90%
He didn't have anything.

00:05:28.360 --> 00:05:29.850 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: So this
is where I begin.

00:05:29.850 --> 00:05:32.010 align:middle line:84%
Part of my job in
software development

00:05:32.010 --> 00:05:35.860 align:middle line:84%
was in writing pattern
recognition software.

00:05:35.860 --> 00:05:37.952 align:middle line:84%
And I've searched patterns
ever since I was a kid.

00:05:37.952 --> 00:05:39.410 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So you
applied it to this?

00:05:39.410 --> 00:05:39.500 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Sure.

00:05:39.500 --> 00:05:40.880 align:middle line:90%
It comes very naturally for me.

00:05:40.880 --> 00:05:43.970 align:middle line:84%
I used to look at
flashing patterns

00:05:43.970 --> 00:05:45.927 align:middle line:84%
on blinking lights
on Christmas trees.

00:05:45.927 --> 00:05:46.510 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:05:46.510 --> 00:05:48.676 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: I mean, you know,
you see them everywhere.

00:05:48.676 --> 00:05:52.180 align:middle line:84%
So I thought, if there
are patterns in nature

00:05:52.180 --> 00:05:56.580 align:middle line:84%
and we are nature, they
should show up in our DNA.

00:05:56.580 --> 00:05:59.370 align:middle line:84%
And it was in the '80s
when the DNA databases,

00:05:59.370 --> 00:06:01.570 align:middle line:84%
we could actually
begin to access them

00:06:01.570 --> 00:06:04.640 align:middle line:84%
without being part of
the research projects.

00:06:04.640 --> 00:06:06.430 align:middle line:84%
So to make a long
story really brief,

00:06:06.430 --> 00:06:12.120 align:middle line:84%
what I found was in one of
the most obscure and ancient

00:06:12.120 --> 00:06:14.804 align:middle line:84%
of the texts, a book called
"The Sefer Yetzirah."

00:06:14.804 --> 00:06:15.720 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: What is that?

00:06:15.720 --> 00:06:17.850 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: It is a Hebrew
text that has only

00:06:17.850 --> 00:06:20.630 align:middle line:84%
been translated a couple of
times by a couple of authors

00:06:20.630 --> 00:06:22.270 align:middle line:90%
into English.

00:06:22.270 --> 00:06:24.562 align:middle line:84%
It's so mysterious, George,
that very few scholars even

00:06:24.562 --> 00:06:26.228 align:middle line:84%
want to talk about
it because they don't

00:06:26.228 --> 00:06:27.420 align:middle line:90%
know what to say about it.

00:06:27.420 --> 00:06:28.300 align:middle line:90%
It's a brief text.

00:06:28.300 --> 00:06:29.650 align:middle line:90%
It's only about 2,000 lines.

00:06:29.650 --> 00:06:30.450 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: All right.

00:06:30.450 --> 00:06:33.700 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: And it is written
as if an observer were present

00:06:33.700 --> 00:06:37.549 align:middle line:84%
the day that the Creator
created humankind step-by-step.

00:06:37.549 --> 00:06:38.090 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Huh.

00:06:38.090 --> 00:06:39.760 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: However, it's
written in a language--

00:06:39.760 --> 00:06:40.960 align:middle line:90%
it doesn't make a lot of sense.

00:06:40.960 --> 00:06:42.870 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Is it like Genesis
or totally different?

00:06:42.870 --> 00:06:44.661 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: It's very
different from Genesis.

00:06:44.661 --> 00:06:47.070 align:middle line:84%
I think Genesis
probably partially

00:06:47.070 --> 00:06:51.070 align:middle line:84%
derived from this text,
"The Sefer Yetzirah," which

00:06:51.070 --> 00:06:52.070 align:middle line:90%
is the book of creation.

00:06:52.070 --> 00:06:54.770 align:middle line:84%
It literally translates
to "the book of creation."

00:06:54.770 --> 00:06:59.951 align:middle line:84%
So it was as if someone were
watching the Creator actually

00:06:59.951 --> 00:07:00.950 align:middle line:90%
create the first person.

00:07:00.950 --> 00:07:02.090 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Doing what he did.

00:07:02.090 --> 00:07:03.440 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Doing what he did.

00:07:03.440 --> 00:07:06.840 align:middle line:84%
But it is not written
scientifically.

00:07:06.840 --> 00:07:10.580 align:middle line:84%
The bottom line to
what the text is saying

00:07:10.580 --> 00:07:16.300 align:middle line:84%
is that through language,
humankind was created.

00:07:16.300 --> 00:07:17.910 align:middle line:84%
And that doesn't
make a lot of sense--

00:07:17.910 --> 00:07:18.826 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Explain that.

00:07:18.826 --> 00:07:20.440 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: --if you
take it literally.

00:07:20.440 --> 00:07:23.270 align:middle line:84%
But as I began to
follow the instructions

00:07:23.270 --> 00:07:27.480 align:middle line:84%
as the author created them in
this text-- and this, George,

00:07:27.480 --> 00:07:30.690 align:middle line:84%
to me, this is the
power of transcending

00:07:30.690 --> 00:07:33.480 align:middle line:84%
the boundaries between
science and spirituality.

00:07:33.480 --> 00:07:37.957 align:middle line:84%
Because if a scientist only
looked at the elements of life,

00:07:37.957 --> 00:07:39.290 align:middle line:90%
you'd never make this discovery.

00:07:39.290 --> 00:07:41.000 align:middle line:84%
If you only look at
the spiritual text,

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:42.930 align:middle line:84%
you would never
make this discovery.

00:07:42.930 --> 00:07:46.390 align:middle line:84%
But it's by blending the
two together and allowing

00:07:46.390 --> 00:07:48.050 align:middle line:90%
them to tell the story.

00:07:48.050 --> 00:07:50.850 align:middle line:84%
So we, today, in
modern science, we

00:07:50.850 --> 00:07:55.710 align:middle line:84%
talk about life as the
result of elements.

00:07:55.710 --> 00:07:59.020 align:middle line:84%
And we describe elements
through word and through number.

00:07:59.020 --> 00:08:01.080 align:middle line:84%
So we have the periodic
table, for example.

00:08:01.080 --> 00:08:04.040 align:middle line:84%
Hydrogen, nitrogen,
oxygen, carbon

00:08:04.040 --> 00:08:06.060 align:middle line:90%
makes up the DNA of our bodies.

00:08:06.060 --> 00:08:07.346 align:middle line:90%
Those are the words.

00:08:07.346 --> 00:08:08.720 align:middle line:84%
And for every one
of those words,

00:08:08.720 --> 00:08:10.920 align:middle line:84%
there are a lot of numbers
that may be applied.

00:08:10.920 --> 00:08:13.240 align:middle line:84%
There are 17 different
numeric parameters

00:08:13.240 --> 00:08:15.670 align:middle line:90%
that go with each of those.

00:08:15.670 --> 00:08:16.700 align:middle line:90%
So put that aside.

00:08:16.700 --> 00:08:19.560 align:middle line:84%
When you go back into the
ancient text and "The Sefer

00:08:19.560 --> 00:08:22.860 align:middle line:84%
Yetzirah" specifically, they
did exactly the same thing.

00:08:22.860 --> 00:08:26.120 align:middle line:84%
They talked about the
power of the letters

00:08:26.120 --> 00:08:28.770 align:middle line:90%
of very specific alphabets.

00:08:28.770 --> 00:08:31.440 align:middle line:84%
Now it doesn't make a lot
of sense to modern scholars

00:08:31.440 --> 00:08:35.990 align:middle line:84%
until we begin to understand
that every ancient alphabet--

00:08:35.990 --> 00:08:41.500 align:middle line:84%
bar none that I have found so
far-- has always, from day one,

00:08:41.500 --> 00:08:44.902 align:middle line:84%
with each letter, had a number,
a mysterious number, associated

00:08:44.902 --> 00:08:45.610 align:middle line:90%
with the letters.

00:08:45.610 --> 00:08:47.030 align:middle line:84%
We don't know where
the numbers came from.

00:08:47.030 --> 00:08:47.785 align:middle line:90%
They never change.

00:08:47.785 --> 00:08:49.780 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: A code?

00:08:49.780 --> 00:08:52.100 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: It's a
unique, numeric code.

00:08:52.100 --> 00:08:55.130 align:middle line:84%
The study of that code
is called Gematria,

00:08:55.130 --> 00:08:56.800 align:middle line:90%
and it was actually formalized.

00:08:56.800 --> 00:08:59.580 align:middle line:84%
The laws, 32 laws,
of Gematria were

00:08:59.580 --> 00:09:01.630 align:middle line:90%
formed in the second century.

00:09:01.630 --> 00:09:04.460 align:middle line:84%
They were formalized
in the second century.

00:09:04.460 --> 00:09:08.020 align:middle line:84%
And the only way Gematria works
is you cannot deviate from

00:09:08.020 --> 00:09:08.520 align:middle line:90%
these laws.

00:09:08.520 --> 00:09:11.900 align:middle line:84%
There are specific laws
that apply to the numbers.

00:09:11.900 --> 00:09:14.860 align:middle line:84%
So our ancestors were
also talking about life

00:09:14.860 --> 00:09:17.030 align:middle line:90%
using words and numbers.

00:09:17.030 --> 00:09:18.770 align:middle line:84%
So they had the letters
of the alphabets

00:09:18.770 --> 00:09:20.230 align:middle line:90%
and this mysterious number.

00:09:20.230 --> 00:09:21.757 align:middle line:90%
We're using the periodic table.

00:09:21.757 --> 00:09:23.090 align:middle line:90%
We got a whole bunch of numbers.

00:09:23.090 --> 00:09:23.800 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:09:23.800 --> 00:09:26.730 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: My job was to find
out which of those numbers

00:09:26.730 --> 00:09:29.360 align:middle line:84%
equates to the numbers
in the ancient alphabets.

00:09:29.360 --> 00:09:31.890 align:middle line:84%
And if I could do
that, my thinking was,

00:09:31.890 --> 00:09:36.040 align:middle line:84%
it would be possible to look
at human DNA-- carbon, oxygen,

00:09:36.040 --> 00:09:39.230 align:middle line:84%
hydrogen, nitrogen and
different combinations of that--

00:09:39.230 --> 00:09:43.700 align:middle line:84%
and substitute the ancient
letters for the numbers

00:09:43.700 --> 00:09:47.080 align:middle line:90%
based upon this correlation.

00:09:47.080 --> 00:09:49.920 align:middle line:84%
This, in retrospect,
it was simple.

00:09:49.920 --> 00:09:52.490 align:middle line:84%
But not knowing
that, it took years.

00:09:52.490 --> 00:09:53.570 align:middle line:90%
It took me 12 years--

00:09:53.570 --> 00:09:54.340 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And did you break it?

00:09:54.340 --> 00:09:55.950 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: --to find
what we now know

00:09:55.950 --> 00:09:59.120 align:middle line:84%
is that the atomic mass of
the elements, the numbers

00:09:59.120 --> 00:10:01.130 align:middle line:84%
of the atomic mass
are the numbers that

00:10:01.130 --> 00:10:05.050 align:middle line:84%
equate to the mysterious letters
in the ancient alphabets.

00:10:05.050 --> 00:10:10.330 align:middle line:84%
What that means is when you
look at human DNA or the DNA

00:10:10.330 --> 00:10:14.920 align:middle line:84%
of any life, it is made of
hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen,

00:10:14.920 --> 00:10:15.870 align:middle line:90%
carbon.

00:10:15.870 --> 00:10:19.700 align:middle line:84%
And using Gematria, the
numbers that equate to those

00:10:19.700 --> 00:10:23.969 align:middle line:84%
become one, five,
six, and three.

00:10:23.969 --> 00:10:25.010 align:middle line:90%
Three is with the carbon.

00:10:25.010 --> 00:10:28.870 align:middle line:84%
And when you then take a table,
one of the ancient tables,

00:10:28.870 --> 00:10:31.390 align:middle line:84%
and you're able to
correlate those numbers

00:10:31.390 --> 00:10:35.692 align:middle line:84%
with the letters, what we find,
George, is that human DNA is--

00:10:35.692 --> 00:10:36.400 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: A match?

00:10:36.400 --> 00:10:39.060 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Our genome
is built in layers.

00:10:39.060 --> 00:10:42.800 align:middle line:84%
And at the top layer-- it's like
every book has an introduction.

00:10:42.800 --> 00:10:46.050 align:middle line:84%
The introduction in
every cell of every form

00:10:46.050 --> 00:10:51.000 align:middle line:84%
of life, carbon-based DNA,
the introduction is the same.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:53.630 align:middle line:84%
And the first
translation literally

00:10:53.630 --> 00:10:59.520 align:middle line:84%
reads-- literal-- "God
eternal within the body."

00:10:59.520 --> 00:11:02.600 align:middle line:90%
God eternal within the body.

00:11:02.600 --> 00:11:06.380 align:middle line:84%
And God that is
depicted in the DNA

00:11:06.380 --> 00:11:10.960 align:middle line:84%
is actually spelled the
way that the name of God

00:11:10.960 --> 00:11:14.330 align:middle line:84%
was spelled in the
ancient text before it

00:11:14.330 --> 00:11:17.390 align:middle line:90%
was removed 6,800 times.

00:11:17.390 --> 00:11:21.520 align:middle line:84%
In the Torah, for example, the
sacred name of God is believed

00:11:21.520 --> 00:11:24.340 align:middle line:84%
to be so sacred it cannot
be written in its entirety.

00:11:24.340 --> 00:11:26.600 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Why put it in a code?

00:11:26.600 --> 00:11:29.070 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: You know,
this was-- so first,

00:11:29.070 --> 00:11:32.170 align:middle line:84%
as a scientist, what
I have to say is this.

00:11:32.170 --> 00:11:33.767 align:middle line:84%
People say, why
is the code there?

00:11:33.767 --> 00:11:34.350 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:11:34.350 --> 00:11:35.880 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: And I
say, I don't know.

00:11:35.880 --> 00:11:38.690 align:middle line:84%
All I know is that when
I follow the instructions

00:11:38.690 --> 00:11:41.614 align:middle line:84%
in a 3,000-year-old text and I
applied to the periodic table--

00:11:41.614 --> 00:11:42.530 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: There it was.

00:11:42.530 --> 00:11:43.904 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: --this
is what we have.

00:11:43.904 --> 00:11:45.602 align:middle line:90%
Next question, is a coincidence?

00:11:45.602 --> 00:11:47.060 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: There are
no coincidences!

00:11:47.060 --> 00:11:47.643 align:middle line:90%
You know that.

00:11:47.643 --> 00:11:49.160 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Well, I
had a statistician

00:11:49.160 --> 00:11:50.210 align:middle line:90%
run the numbers for me.

00:11:50.210 --> 00:11:55.945 align:middle line:84%
And the odds of this happening
by chance are 1 to 234,256.

00:11:55.945 --> 00:11:57.090 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:11:57.090 --> 00:12:02.325 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: 234,256
to 1, or 0.00041%--

00:12:02.325 --> 00:12:02.950 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:12:02.950 --> 00:12:04.850 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: --those are
the odds that it's--

00:12:04.850 --> 00:12:06.170 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Just random.

00:12:06.170 --> 00:12:07.200 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: --just random.

00:12:07.200 --> 00:12:10.080 align:middle line:84%
Now those aren't
astronomical odds.

00:12:10.080 --> 00:12:12.330 align:middle line:84%
I thought it might be
like one to a bajillion.

00:12:12.330 --> 00:12:13.320 align:middle line:90%
You know?

00:12:13.320 --> 00:12:14.764 align:middle line:90%
But when you take into account--

00:12:14.764 --> 00:12:15.930 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: They're still high.

00:12:15.930 --> 00:12:20.640 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Not only is
the language there,

00:12:20.640 --> 00:12:23.920 align:middle line:84%
but when you take into
account what the words say,

00:12:23.920 --> 00:12:25.720 align:middle line:84%
that those words
actually have meaning,

00:12:25.720 --> 00:12:27.299 align:middle line:90%
"God eternal within the body."

00:12:27.299 --> 00:12:28.590 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And they all say that?

00:12:28.590 --> 00:12:30.840 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: The first
letter in all human DNA,

00:12:30.840 --> 00:12:36.814 align:middle line:84%
if you can look at what's
called the genetic code, CTAG,

00:12:36.814 --> 00:12:39.480 align:middle line:84%
every one of those is made up of
combinations of carbon, oxygen,

00:12:39.480 --> 00:12:40.380 align:middle line:90%
hydrogen, nitrogen.

00:12:40.380 --> 00:12:41.010 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:12:41.010 --> 00:12:43.224 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: And they
are arranged--

00:12:43.224 --> 00:12:44.890 align:middle line:84%
I don't want to be
really technical when

00:12:44.890 --> 00:12:47.520 align:middle line:84%
I talk about this,
but they're arranged

00:12:47.520 --> 00:12:52.110 align:middle line:84%
different numbers of carbon,
oxygen, hydrogen, nitrogen

00:12:52.110 --> 00:12:53.300 align:middle line:90%
atoms.

00:12:53.300 --> 00:12:57.940 align:middle line:84%
So within each of the DNA bases
that make our DNA as it is,

00:12:57.940 --> 00:13:01.815 align:middle line:84%
they're different combinations
of CTAG that breakdown

00:13:01.815 --> 00:13:04.900 align:middle line:84%
to different combinations of
"God eternal within the body."

00:13:04.900 --> 00:13:08.570 align:middle line:84%
And the God within
ourselves, within our DNA,

00:13:08.570 --> 00:13:12.950 align:middle line:84%
is literally the same
spelling of the God

00:13:12.950 --> 00:13:15.404 align:middle line:90%
that was taken from those texts.

00:13:15.404 --> 00:13:16.320 align:middle line:90%
Now here's the beauty.

00:13:16.320 --> 00:13:17.400 align:middle line:90%
I just have to say this.

00:13:17.400 --> 00:13:18.191 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: All right.

00:13:18.191 --> 00:13:20.810 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: My first
fear was I found it

00:13:20.810 --> 00:13:22.160 align:middle line:90%
in the Hebrew language.

00:13:22.160 --> 00:13:25.330 align:middle line:84%
And I said, does that
mean-- could it actually

00:13:25.330 --> 00:13:29.170 align:middle line:84%
be divisive if it only
is found in one language?

00:13:29.170 --> 00:13:33.060 align:middle line:84%
And when the research went to
its fruition, what we found

00:13:33.060 --> 00:13:36.940 align:middle line:84%
is it is in Hebrew and
Aramaic and Sanskrit,

00:13:36.940 --> 00:13:38.230 align:middle line:90%
three of the root languages.

00:13:38.230 --> 00:13:39.230 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: The same thing?

00:13:39.230 --> 00:13:40.720 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Exactly
the same thing.

00:13:40.720 --> 00:13:44.050 align:middle line:84%
So in Hebrew,
Aramaic, and Sanskrit,

00:13:44.050 --> 00:13:47.650 align:middle line:84%
the code for those letters
translates precisely the same

00:13:47.650 --> 00:13:48.430 align:middle line:90%
in the human DNA.

00:13:48.430 --> 00:13:50.530 align:middle line:90%
That's the first layer.

00:13:50.530 --> 00:13:53.840 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: In your
opinion, that slogan,

00:13:53.840 --> 00:13:57.730 align:middle line:84%
"God eternal is in the
body," what did that mean?

00:13:57.730 --> 00:14:02.640 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: What it tells me
is because the odds of that

00:14:02.640 --> 00:14:05.524 align:middle line:90%
happening by chance are--

00:14:05.524 --> 00:14:06.440 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Astronomical.

00:14:06.440 --> 00:14:07.390 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: --are steep.

00:14:07.390 --> 00:14:09.410 align:middle line:84%
It tells me there's
an intentionality.

00:14:09.410 --> 00:14:11.620 align:middle line:84%
Now who or what, I don't
know the answer to that.

00:14:11.620 --> 00:14:15.940 align:middle line:84%
But it tells me that the
DNA, the way it's formed,

00:14:15.940 --> 00:14:20.000 align:middle line:90%
is intentional.

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:24.220 align:middle line:84%
And then I began to think,
in our modern world,

00:14:24.220 --> 00:14:25.120 align:middle line:90%
we're creators.

00:14:25.120 --> 00:14:26.110 align:middle line:90%
We're artists.

00:14:26.110 --> 00:14:29.030 align:middle line:84%
Whenever we create something
that we're proud of, when we're

00:14:29.030 --> 00:14:30.652 align:middle line:84%
finished, what's
the last thing we

00:14:30.652 --> 00:14:31.860 align:middle line:90%
do when we finish it, George?

00:14:31.860 --> 00:14:32.250 align:middle line:90%
You tell me.

00:14:32.250 --> 00:14:34.120 align:middle line:84%
What is the last thing
we do with something?

00:14:34.120 --> 00:14:36.470 align:middle line:84%
We finish a painting,
and what's the last thing

00:14:36.470 --> 00:14:37.530 align:middle line:84%
we do when we finish
that painting?

00:14:37.530 --> 00:14:38.404 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: You sign it.

00:14:38.404 --> 00:14:39.840 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: We put our name on it.

00:14:39.840 --> 00:14:42.970 align:middle line:84%
If there's an intentionality
underlying life itself

00:14:42.970 --> 00:14:45.910 align:middle line:84%
and human life specifically,
it would make tremendous sense

00:14:45.910 --> 00:14:48.980 align:middle line:84%
to me that who or
whoever is responsible

00:14:48.980 --> 00:14:51.070 align:middle line:90%
would somehow have left a sign.

00:14:51.070 --> 00:14:52.720 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Is it God's signature?

00:14:52.720 --> 00:14:56.120 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: I believe that
however we define that, whoever

00:14:56.120 --> 00:14:57.710 align:middle line:84%
or whatever we
believe that Creator

00:14:57.710 --> 00:15:02.170 align:middle line:84%
is, my next question is,
why not put it into a text?

00:15:02.170 --> 00:15:03.570 align:middle line:90%
Or into a temple wall?

00:15:03.570 --> 00:15:08.200 align:middle line:84%
And then, my thinking was,
why place that signature

00:15:08.200 --> 00:15:11.360 align:middle line:84%
into something that can crumble
over a few thousand years

00:15:11.360 --> 00:15:12.330 align:middle line:90%
like a temple wall?

00:15:12.330 --> 00:15:15.870 align:middle line:84%
Or into the pages of a
book that can be destroyed?

00:15:15.870 --> 00:15:17.862 align:middle line:84%
Why not put it in
the creation itself?

00:15:17.862 --> 00:15:19.320 align:middle line:84%
And as long as the
creation exists,

00:15:19.320 --> 00:15:21.680 align:middle line:90%
the message exists as well.

00:15:21.680 --> 00:15:23.290 align:middle line:90%
I publish this in 2004.

00:15:23.290 --> 00:15:26.720 align:middle line:84%
Even though the
research was incomplete,

00:15:26.720 --> 00:15:28.440 align:middle line:90%
it was complete to that point.

00:15:28.440 --> 00:15:32.260 align:middle line:84%
And I wanted to share
this with the world.

00:15:32.260 --> 00:15:35.965 align:middle line:84%
2007, Japanese scientists
released a report,

00:15:35.965 --> 00:15:41.800 align:middle line:84%
a peer reviewed report, on the
feasibility of storing data

00:15:41.800 --> 00:15:44.740 align:middle line:90%
in DNA for thousands of years.

00:15:44.740 --> 00:15:47.680 align:middle line:84%
And what they were
looking at is bacteria.

00:15:47.680 --> 00:15:50.800 align:middle line:84%
They were looking at storing
information in bacteria

00:15:50.800 --> 00:15:53.380 align:middle line:84%
and placing the bacteria
in nuclear waste dumps,

00:15:53.380 --> 00:15:53.950 align:middle line:90%
for example.

00:15:53.950 --> 00:15:54.730 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And letting
it sit there.

00:15:54.730 --> 00:15:55.920 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: And
letting it sit there.

00:15:55.920 --> 00:15:58.260 align:middle line:84%
Because the papers might
disintegrate or something else

00:15:58.260 --> 00:15:58.820 align:middle line:90%
might happen.

00:15:58.820 --> 00:16:00.180 align:middle line:90%
But if they could do it.

00:16:00.180 --> 00:16:04.860 align:middle line:84%
So 2007 was the first
time they successfully

00:16:04.860 --> 00:16:08.570 align:middle line:84%
implanted a message into
the DNA of a bacteria.

00:16:08.570 --> 00:16:10.077 align:middle line:90%
And they used bacteria because--

00:16:10.077 --> 00:16:12.160 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Hoping that someone
in the future one day

00:16:12.160 --> 00:16:12.847 align:middle line:90%
would use it?

00:16:12.847 --> 00:16:14.180 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Well, this was a test.

00:16:14.180 --> 00:16:16.620 align:middle line:84%
They used the bacteria because
they have a short lifespan,

00:16:16.620 --> 00:16:18.600 align:middle line:84%
so they can see how
many generations.

00:16:18.600 --> 00:16:18.900 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Would it take.

00:16:18.900 --> 00:16:19.830 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: You know,
for a bacteria,

00:16:19.830 --> 00:16:21.747 align:middle line:84%
the generations may
be just a few days.

00:16:21.747 --> 00:16:22.330 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:16:22.330 --> 00:16:26.242 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: The code they
put into the DNA, it was--

00:16:26.242 --> 00:16:27.950 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Don't say it
was the same thing.

00:16:27.950 --> 00:16:28.491 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: No.

00:16:28.491 --> 00:16:29.610 align:middle line:90%
It was Einstein's theory.

00:16:29.610 --> 00:16:33.990 align:middle line:84%
It was E equals mc
squared in the year 1905.

00:16:33.990 --> 00:16:36.350 align:middle line:90%
They encoded that into the DNA.

00:16:36.350 --> 00:16:41.221 align:middle line:84%
They allowed the DNA to
replicate for 25 generations.

00:16:41.221 --> 00:16:42.220 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: With that code.

00:16:42.220 --> 00:16:43.220 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: With the code.

00:16:43.220 --> 00:16:44.720 align:middle line:90%
They pulled the code right out.

00:16:44.720 --> 00:16:45.120 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: How bizarre.

00:16:45.120 --> 00:16:46.286 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Completely intact.

00:16:46.286 --> 00:16:49.350 align:middle line:84%
So what they're
now demonstrating

00:16:49.350 --> 00:16:53.390 align:middle line:84%
purely in the scientific
realm is the feasibility

00:16:53.390 --> 00:16:59.180 align:middle line:84%
of storing literal information
in the genome, in the DNA.

00:16:59.180 --> 00:17:01.500 align:middle line:84%
And it remains
intact for as long

00:17:01.500 --> 00:17:03.570 align:middle line:90%
as the organism remains intact.

00:17:03.570 --> 00:17:05.670 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, here's
the puzzling part.

00:17:05.670 --> 00:17:07.619 align:middle line:84%
If you put a code
in there, you're

00:17:07.619 --> 00:17:09.690 align:middle line:84%
doing it for one
of several reasons.

00:17:09.690 --> 00:17:11.940 align:middle line:90%
One, you're hiding it.

00:17:11.940 --> 00:17:14.319 align:middle line:84%
Or two, you're trying
to pass information

00:17:14.319 --> 00:17:16.890 align:middle line:90%
on to some future generation.

00:17:16.890 --> 00:17:19.500 align:middle line:84%
So let's assume that
that's what that is.

00:17:19.500 --> 00:17:20.680 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Yeah.

00:17:20.680 --> 00:17:24.740 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: When we extract it
and we get that code, what

00:17:24.740 --> 00:17:25.921 align:middle line:90%
do we do with it?

00:17:25.921 --> 00:17:26.670 align:middle line:90%
What does it mean?

00:17:26.670 --> 00:17:28.794 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: I think it depends
on what the code says.

00:17:28.794 --> 00:17:29.510 align:middle line:90%
Now, we know.

00:17:29.510 --> 00:17:31.990 align:middle line:84%
And the work is progressing
from this point.

00:17:31.990 --> 00:17:36.057 align:middle line:84%
And in 2015, another layer will
have been completely decoded.

00:17:36.057 --> 00:17:38.265 align:middle line:84%
Then hopefully, you and I
can have this conversation,

00:17:38.265 --> 00:17:41.410 align:middle line:84%
and I'll share
what we find next.

00:17:41.410 --> 00:17:45.800 align:middle line:84%
The point is that there
is a message encoded

00:17:45.800 --> 00:17:47.850 align:middle line:84%
into the DNA of all
human life that tells us

00:17:47.850 --> 00:17:51.700 align:middle line:84%
beyond any reasonable doubt that
the differences that divide us

00:17:51.700 --> 00:17:54.640 align:middle line:84%
now are superficial
differences and that we

00:17:54.640 --> 00:17:57.235 align:middle line:84%
have a common origin,
a common ancestry.

