There's another branch of
work that this follows up on,

00:26:15.850 --> 00:26:18.120 align:middle line:84%
and it is the study
of whether or not

00:26:18.120 --> 00:26:21.640 align:middle line:84%
we are living in a simulation
or a virtual reality.

00:26:21.640 --> 00:26:25.322 align:middle line:84%
And there is a
degreed course in one

00:26:25.322 --> 00:26:26.780 align:middle line:84%
of the large eastern
universities--

00:26:26.780 --> 00:26:27.620 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Really?

00:26:27.620 --> 00:26:29.453 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: --in philosophy
that you can take.

00:26:29.453 --> 00:26:32.190 align:middle line:84%
And the title of the course is
"Are We Living a Simulation?"

00:26:32.190 --> 00:26:35.370 align:middle line:84%
And to make a long story very
brief, what they did was they

00:26:35.370 --> 00:26:38.320 align:middle line:84%
took a very complex
computer algorithm,

00:26:38.320 --> 00:26:40.400 align:middle line:84%
plugged in all
kinds of variables

00:26:40.400 --> 00:26:43.530 align:middle line:84%
about human population
and trajectories

00:26:43.530 --> 00:26:46.720 align:middle line:84%
and economies and families
and religious beliefs--

00:26:46.720 --> 00:26:48.570 align:middle line:90%
all about life.

00:26:48.570 --> 00:26:53.620 align:middle line:84%
And the bottom line is there's
over a 93% chance that we

00:26:53.620 --> 00:26:55.660 align:middle line:90%
are living a simulation.

00:26:55.660 --> 00:26:57.570 align:middle line:84%
Now if you step
into a simulation,

00:26:57.570 --> 00:26:59.514 align:middle line:84%
a virtual environment,
in Disneyland,

00:26:59.514 --> 00:27:00.930 align:middle line:84%
you can do that
today and not even

00:27:00.930 --> 00:27:02.950 align:middle line:84%
really know that
that's where you are.

00:27:02.950 --> 00:27:05.050 align:middle line:84%
And we've only had
computers about 60 years.

00:27:05.050 --> 00:27:07.740 align:middle line:84%
If you take the
archaeology that's

00:27:07.740 --> 00:27:10.620 align:middle line:84%
showing the existence of
advanced technological

00:27:10.620 --> 00:27:13.050 align:middle line:84%
civilizations
thousands of years,

00:27:13.050 --> 00:27:15.360 align:middle line:84%
where would we be
if we had thousands

00:27:15.360 --> 00:27:19.595 align:middle line:84%
of years of computer science to
build that kind of simulation?

00:27:19.595 --> 00:27:20.220 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:27:20.220 --> 00:27:23.200 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: And the question
comes, why would we do this?

00:27:23.200 --> 00:27:26.450 align:middle line:84%
And the answer for me
is that every simulation

00:27:26.450 --> 00:27:32.880 align:middle line:84%
is built to help the people
in the simulation become very

00:27:32.880 --> 00:27:35.330 align:middle line:84%
well-adapted to
somewhere that they're

00:27:35.330 --> 00:27:37.870 align:middle line:84%
going to be when the
simulation no longer exists.

00:27:37.870 --> 00:27:41.540 align:middle line:84%
The simulation's a safe place
to make mistakes and learn

00:27:41.540 --> 00:27:45.040 align:middle line:84%
that power if we are in fact,
on Earth, living a simulation.

00:27:45.040 --> 00:27:46.880 align:middle line:84%
And our most
cherished traditions

00:27:46.880 --> 00:27:49.307 align:middle line:84%
tell us that we're on
our way somewhere else.

00:27:49.307 --> 00:27:49.890 align:middle line:90%
This isn't it.

00:27:49.890 --> 00:27:50.723 align:middle line:90%
This is an illusion.

00:27:50.723 --> 00:27:51.890 align:middle line:90%
This is temporary.

00:27:51.890 --> 00:27:53.824 align:middle line:90%
In general, they say that.

00:27:53.824 --> 00:27:56.240 align:middle line:84%
Then, I think we have to look
at what those traditions are

00:27:56.240 --> 00:27:56.750 align:middle line:90%
telling us.

00:27:56.750 --> 00:27:59.230 align:middle line:84%
And they're teaching us
about our relationship

00:27:59.230 --> 00:28:06.230 align:middle line:84%
to reality, to quantum reality,
to emotions and emotions

00:28:06.230 --> 00:28:08.095 align:middle line:90%
of the heart, to create--

00:28:08.095 --> 00:28:08.720 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:28:08.720 --> 00:28:11.180 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: --and heal in our
bodies and the world around us.

00:28:11.180 --> 00:28:13.460 align:middle line:84%
And if we master
those, maybe that's

00:28:13.460 --> 00:28:15.790 align:middle line:84%
what this simulation
is all about.

00:28:15.790 --> 00:28:20.320 align:middle line:84%
God eternal within
the body, may be

00:28:20.320 --> 00:28:23.340 align:middle line:84%
the architect that has helped
to create this simulation.

00:28:23.340 --> 00:28:24.799 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Do you
ever get frustrated

00:28:24.799 --> 00:28:26.256 align:middle line:84%
that we don't have
the answers yet?

00:28:26.256 --> 00:28:27.350 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: I don't, George.

00:28:27.350 --> 00:28:27.850 align:middle line:90%
I don't.

00:28:27.850 --> 00:28:30.610 align:middle line:84%
Because what it tells
me is-- and what

00:28:30.610 --> 00:28:32.440 align:middle line:84%
I've come to
understand-- is that when

00:28:32.440 --> 00:28:38.530 align:middle line:84%
we are truly ready for that
information, it's right there.

00:28:38.530 --> 00:28:39.840 align:middle line:90%
This is a perfect example.

00:28:39.840 --> 00:28:43.540 align:middle line:84%
This has been around
for 200,000 years.

00:28:43.540 --> 00:28:44.740 align:middle line:90%
It's only when--

00:28:44.740 --> 00:28:47.510 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Only to be discovered,
though, by those who look.

00:28:47.510 --> 00:28:50.780 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Or when our technology
reaches the point that it gives

00:28:50.780 --> 00:28:51.415 align:middle line:90%
us the tools--

00:28:51.415 --> 00:28:51.790 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: True.

00:28:51.790 --> 00:28:52.850 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: --to take a peek.

00:28:52.850 --> 00:28:53.890 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It's almost
like that code

00:28:53.890 --> 00:28:55.780 align:middle line:84%
we sent out on one
of the Viking craft.

00:28:55.780 --> 00:28:56.010 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: I know.

00:28:56.010 --> 00:28:56.720 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right?

00:28:56.720 --> 00:28:57.400 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Yeah.

00:28:57.400 --> 00:29:00.160 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Which Stephen
Hawking said, don't do!

00:29:00.160 --> 00:29:02.380 align:middle line:84%
Because he's afraid
that they'll come here.

00:29:02.380 --> 00:29:05.446 align:middle line:84%
And he's not so sure
they're very benevolent.

00:29:05.446 --> 00:29:06.970 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: Yeah.

00:29:06.970 --> 00:29:08.000 align:middle line:90%
It was interesting.

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:11.040 align:middle line:84%
I actually talk about that code
in the book "The God Code."

00:29:11.040 --> 00:29:12.460 align:middle line:90%
What is it that we said?

00:29:12.460 --> 00:29:13.547 align:middle line:90%
Who did we write it to?

00:29:13.547 --> 00:29:14.630 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And who finds it?

00:29:14.630 --> 00:29:16.379 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: And how would
it be interpreted?

00:29:16.379 --> 00:29:17.180 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:29:17.180 --> 00:29:19.520 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: So it makes
perfect sense to me.

00:29:19.520 --> 00:29:24.300 align:middle line:84%
If we are the product
of intentional creation,

00:29:24.300 --> 00:29:26.130 align:middle line:84%
that the Creator, who
or whatever that is,

00:29:26.130 --> 00:29:28.670 align:middle line:84%
would somehow leave
a mark letting

00:29:28.670 --> 00:29:31.399 align:middle line:84%
us know when we have the
ability to find that.

00:29:31.399 --> 00:29:32.440 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It is brilliant.

00:29:32.440 --> 00:29:36.660 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: And I can't think of
a more honoring way to honor who

00:29:36.660 --> 00:29:39.500 align:middle line:84%
or what that Creator is
than to take that code,

00:29:39.500 --> 00:29:42.500 align:middle line:84%
read it, and maybe communicate
back the other way.

00:29:42.500 --> 00:29:44.479 align:middle line:84%
And I think we are on
our way to doing that.

00:29:44.479 --> 00:29:45.520 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: I think so, too.

00:29:45.520 --> 00:29:46.780 align:middle line:84%
Gregg, thanks for being
on "Beyond Belief."

00:29:46.780 --> 00:29:47.810 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: Oh, George,
thank you for this.

00:29:47.810 --> 00:29:48.770 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: You're so enlightening.

00:29:48.770 --> 00:29:49.430 align:middle line:90%
You really are.

00:29:49.430 --> 00:29:50.020 align:middle line:84%
>>BRADEN: I've enjoyed
this tremendously.

00:29:50.020 --> 00:29:51.917 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You bring a
different perspective

00:29:51.917 --> 00:29:54.375 align:middle line:84%
to just about everything we've
talked about over the years.

00:29:54.375 --> 00:29:55.190 align:middle line:90%
I appreciate it.

00:29:55.190 --> 00:29:55.860 align:middle line:90%
>>BRADEN: I appreciate you.

00:29:55.860 --> 00:29:56.810 align:middle line:90%
Thank you for today.

00:29:56.810 --> 00:29:59.226 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You know, as we've
talked, do we get that answer?

00:29:59.226 --> 00:29:59.890 align:middle line:90%
Who are we?

00:29:59.890 --> 00:30:01.950 align:middle line:90%
Why are we here?

00:30:01.950 --> 00:30:05.870 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes I wonder, maybe
we won't get that answer.

00:30:05.870 --> 00:30:08.340 align:middle line:84%
But we'll continue
striving for it.

00:30:08.340 --> 00:30:10.560 align:middle line:84%
And I think that'll
make us a better person.

00:30:10.560 --> 00:30:15.130 align:middle line:84%
I'm George Noory, and
this is "Beyond Belief."

